mpower,Design and Validation of a New Diagnostic Tool for the Differentiation of Pathological Voices in Parkinsonian Patients,https://doi.org/10.26262/heal.auth.ir.325427,openalex_mpower_T_ml_top350.csv,https://openalex.org/W3217568535,2020,include_any_use,True,50811,html_plus_pdf,,Handcrafted feature pipelines; Learned representation pipelines; Sequential predictive pipelines,3,1,1,0,1,0,"wel ’aah’ of 43 participants from the National Center for Voice and Speech database. By cross referencing four diﬀerent feature selection algorithms (least absolute shrinkage and selection operator [16], minimum redundancy maximum relevance [17], RELIEF [18], and local learning-based feature selection [19]), the mos","inear resulting in better performance. A batch normalization layer was combined with the dilated CNN to form an upgrade feature learning block and provide more stability to the network. The method was implemented on 2 databases, the Interactive Emotional Dyadic Motion Capture Corpus [24] and the Berlin Database of",,"y 1 state-of-the-art techniques in speech recognition has raked gains in voice pathology detection. For example, linear prediction coeﬃcients extracted from utterances were used as features and the receiver operating character- istic (ROC) curve of the linear classiﬁer for vocal fold paralysis and vocal fold edema detection was derived in [5]. Such a linear classiﬁer stemmed from the Bayes classiﬁer, when Gaussian class conditional probability den- sity functions with equal covariance matrices were assumed. The optimal operating point of the linear classiﬁer was speciﬁed with and without reject option. The reject option was shown to yield statistically signiﬁcant im- provements in the accuracy of detecting the voice pathologies under study [5]. Other frequently used features are the mel-Frequency cepstral coeﬃcients (MFCCs). MFCCs can simulate the human hearing mechanism but are not easily interpretable in relation to laryngeal physiology [6]. In [7], feature extraction methods from the Audio-Visual Emotion Recognition Challenge [8] were used with a Gradient Boosted Decision Tree classiﬁer for Parkin- son’s diagnosis (i.e., a two-class problem) on the mobile Parkinson Disease (mPower) database [9]. An accuracy of 86% was reported. A neurocomputa- tional framework was presented to model the speech production process [10]. The model generated biomarkers of disease by modeling vocal source control with two muscle parameters and their coordination. The derived features were applied to both the Audio-Visual Emotion Recognition Challenge and the mPower databases. A Fish-er vector image representation method was tested on the PC-GITA Spanish language dataset to encode the gradients of the log-likelihood of features under the Gaussian Mixture Models. That method combined with a Support Vector Machine (SVM) classiﬁer resulted in 84% accuracy on Parkinson detection of pathological speech versus (vs.) healthy [11]. The rapid progress of Deep Neural Networks brought forth novel ap- proaches to speech analysis. Among the deep learning architectures, the ones with the most discriminative potential are the Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) [12]. CNNs are fast and very eﬃcient in image classiﬁ- cation tasks and require little preprocessing, which results in a reduction of the human error factor. Advantages like these, make them ideal for medi- cal image analysis, like breast cancer [13] and diabetic retinopathy detection [14]. 2 1.2 Thesis goals In this paper, a CNN is used to detect pathological from healthy voices. As input to the CNN, mel-spectrograms are extracted from voice samples recorded by a smartphone. A mel-spectrogram captures the resonating fre- quencies of vocal tract and their variation in the temporal domain. It unlocks the vocal tract information of a pathological physiology [6]. The proposed model succeeds to detect Parkinson patients from voice recorded in ambient conditions. Moreover, the proposed model, trained for detecting PD by pro- cessing mPower recordings, can also detect 6 voice pathologies (i.e., healthy vs. pathological) in experiments conducted on recordings from Saarbrueken Voice Database (SVD). These pathologies are dysphonia, functional dyspho- nia, hyper functional dysphonia, spasmodic dysphonia, vocal fold polyp, and dysody. 1.3 Thesis structure Chapter 1 summarizes the issues that arise in this ﬁeld of study and the beneﬁts of successful outcomes as well as possible method approaches. Chapter 2 presents the related research that has inspired and guided this experiment in the ﬁeld of natural language processing and the revolutionary innovations it can bring on the medical ﬁeld. Chapter 3 lays the theoretical background of signal analysis and machine learning with deeper focus on the fast Fourier transform and the convolu- tional neural networks. Chapter 4 introduces the proposed method for pathological voice detec- tion. The preprocessing steps and the chosen architecture are discussed. Chapter 5 analyzes the acquired results and comments on the eﬀectiveness of the method. The experimental process is expanded and comparisons are made. 3 Chapter 6 provides the overview of the research and the basic ﬁnds and points to possible future research. 4 Chapter 2 Related Work 2.1 Pathological Voice Detection There have been many studies focused on diﬀerent kinds of pathological speech, featuring various methods of feature analysis. Tsanas et al. used dysphonia measures to develop a detection tool for Parkinson’s disease [15]. The dataset used consisted of 263 recordings of the sustained vowel ’aah’ of 43 participants from the National Center for Voice and Speech database. By cross referencing four diﬀerent feature selection algorithms (least absolute shrinkage and selection operator [16], minimum redundancy maximum relevance [17], RELIEF [18], and local learning-based feature selection [19]), the most often appearing features for each algorithm were selected. Finally a 10 feature subset of dysphonia measures were cho- sen, from the original 132-dimensional feature space, through a voting scheme across feature selection algorithms. Random forest and Support Vector Ma- chine algorithms were implemented to discriminate PD patients from healthy control subjects in a binary task. A 98.6% accuracy score was achieved. A similar method brought forth by Xu et al. implements a feature selec- tion step using L1-norm penalization after a MFCC feature extraction process [20]. The feature reduction aims to increase accuracy as well as speed for the ﬁnal classiﬁcation step. A SVM with a radial basis function kernel achieved an accuracy score of 99%. The dataset comprised of a subset of the mPower database including 1,000 voice recordings. The method was developed to run real time detection on a smartphone device. 5 2.2 CNNs for Voice Recognition Although pathological voice detection is the main focus of this study, the method used is greatly inspired from various speech recognition tasks such as Speech Emotion Recognition (SER) and Speaker Recognition , so it would be a shortfall to not mention some of the existing research in that ﬁeld. In a method proposed by Badshah et al. [21], spectrograms are used as input for a CNN architecture to accomplish SER on the Berlin Database of Emotional Speech [22]. The proposed model consists of a 3 Convolutional layer architecture followed by 3 fully connected layers that end up in a Soft- max layer. An accuracy of over 50% was achieved for 4 of the 7 emotions studied with anger performing the best at 84.21%. A 3-D feature map approach combined with a deep neural architecture is the method proposed by Meng et al. for SER [23]. The Log-Mel spec- trograms are used as the ﬁrst dimension of the 3-D input followed by the deltas and deltas-deltas, which are the functional values of Log-Mel, as the second and third input. The deltas help to incorporate some dynamic infor- mation possibly carried by the signal. The 3-D input was fed into a dilated CNN which uses a dilated kernel to increase the receptive ﬁeld exponentially while keeping the parameter growth linear resulting in better performance. A batch normalization layer was combined with the dilated CNN to form an upgrade feature learning block and provide more stability to the network. The method was implemented on 2 databases, the Interactive Emotional Dyadic Motion Capture Corpus [24] and the Berlin Database of Emotional Speech [22] with an accuracy of 74.96% and 90.37% respectively on a speaker dependent basis. Zhao et al. take advantage of the existing deep architecture of the already trained Res-Net CNN model to improve text-independent speaker veriﬁcation [25]. Using the VoxCeleb corpus [26] for training and evaluating the model and a Microsoft internal test set of a 100 speakers, an improvement of up to 28% percent was achieved in EER reduction compared to the baseline well-trained ResNet. The proposed method consists of the ResNet network combined with an attentive pooling layer intended to make the network more robust. 2.3 CNN Pathological Voice Detection A method developed by Warnita et al. used a gated CNN for Alzheimer’s Disease detection [27] on the Pitt Corpus [28] which is a subset of data acquired from the DementiaBank. The openSMILE feature extractor was 6 used. 4 diﬀerent feature sets were deployed, the INTERSPEECH 2009 Emo- tion Challenge Features (IS09) [29], the INTERSPEECH 2010 Paralinguis- tic Challenge Features (IS10) [30], the INTERSPEECH 2011 Speaker State Challenge Features (IS11) [31] and the INTERSPEECH 2012 Speaker Trait Challenge Features (IS12) [32]. The low-level descriptors extracted include, but are not limited to, pitch, delta coeﬃcients, jitter, loudness and harmonic- to-noise ratio. A Gated CNN was chosen as a classiﬁcation method. The gate mechanism is used to control the ﬂow of information between convolutional layers and has the ability to prevent the vanishing gradient problem. The best result was tures under the Gaussian Mixture Models. That method combined with a Support Vector Machine (SVM) classiﬁer resulted in 84% accuracy on Parkinson detection of pathological speech versus (vs.) healthy [11]. The rapid progress of Deep Neural Networks brought forth novel ap- proaches to speech analysis. Among the deep learning architectures, the ones with the most discriminative potential are the Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) [12]. CNNs are fast and very eﬃcient in image classiﬁ- cation tasks and require little preprocessing, which results in a reduction of the human error factor. Advantages like these, make them ideal for medi- cal image analysis, like breast cancer [13] and diabetic retinopathy detection [14]. 2 1.2 Thesis goals In this paper, a CNN is used to detect pathological from healthy voices. As input to the CNN, mel-spectrograms are extracted from voice samples recorded by a smartphone. A mel-spectrogram captures the resonating fre- quencies of vocal tract and their variation in the temporal domain. It unlocks the vocal tract information of a pathological physiology [6]. The proposed model succeeds to detect Parkinson patients from voice recorded in ambient conditions. Moreover, the proposed model, trained for detecting PD by pro- cessing mPower recordings, can also detect 6 voice pathologies (i.e., healthy vs. pathological) in experiments conducted on recordings from Saarbrueken Voice Database (SVD). These pathologies are dysphonia, functional dyspho- nia, hyper functional dysphonia, spasmodic dysphonia, vocal fold polyp, and dysody. 1.3 Thesis structure Chapter 1 summarizes the issues that arise in this ﬁeld of study and the beneﬁts of successful outcomes as well as possible method approaches. Chapter 2 presents the related research that has inspired and guided this experiment in the ﬁeld of natural language processing and the revolutionary innovations it can bring on the medical ﬁeld. Chapter 3 lays the theoretical backgroun