se including 1,000 voice recordings. The method was developed to run real time detection on a smartphone device. 5 2.2 CNNs for Voice Recognition Although pathological voice detection is the main focus of this study, the method used is greatly inspired from various speech recognition tasks such as Speech Emotion Recognition (SER) and Speaker Recognition , so it would be a shortfall to not mention some of the existing research in that ﬁeld. In a method proposed by Badshah et al. [21], spectrograms are used as input for a CNN architecture to accomplish SER on the Berlin Database of Emotional Speech [22]. The proposed model consists of a 3 Convolutional layer architecture followed by 3 fully connected layers that end up in a Soft- max layer. An accuracy of over 50% was achieved for 4 of the 7 emotions studied with anger performing the best at 84.21%. A 3-D feature map approach combined with a deep neural architecture is the method proposed by Meng et al. for SER [23]. The Log-Mel spec- trograms are used as the ﬁrst dimension of the 3-D input followed by the deltas and deltas-deltas, which are the functional values of Log-Mel, as the second and third input. The deltas help to incorporate some dynamic infor- mation possibly carried by the signal. The 3-D input was fed into a dilated CNN which uses a dilated kernel to increase the receptive ﬁeld exponentially while keeping the parameter growth linear resulting in better performance. A batch normaliza",
