studentlife,Harnessing multimodal graph neural networks to predict graduate employment anxiety,https://doi.org/10.1504/ijict.2026.152383,openalex_studentlife_T_ml_top350.csv,https://openalex.org/W7138898512,2026.0,include_any_use,True,54717,pdf,,Learned representation pipelines; Fusion-centric architectures; Sequential predictive pipelines,3,0,1,1,1,0,,"graph learning module. 3.2.2 Animation learning module This module constitutes the core of the model, designed to learn node embeddings from the dynamic contact network { A1, A2, …, AT} to simulate social buffering effects. We employ a variant of the gated GNN (GGNN) to handle the temporal graph structure, as it e",arch primar ily employed feature-le vel (early) fusion or decision-level (late) fusion strategies. The effectiveness of multimodal fusion is highly dependent on the quality and completeness of data across modalities. When data from a particular modality (such as social contact ne tworks) exhibits severe missing valu,"pying how individual behaviours and social forces wo rk together for mental health checks. Keywords: employment anxiety prediction; multimodal learning; graph neural networks; dynamic social netw orks; digital phenotyping. Reference to this paper should be made as follows: Ouyang, C. (2026) ‘Harnessing multimodal graph neural networks to pred ict graduate employment anxiety’, Int. J. Information and Communication Technology , Vol. 27, No. 22, pp.54–71. Biographical notes: Chenghui Ouyang is a Lecturer at the School of Logistics and E-Commerce, Zhejiang Wanli University. He earned his Bachelor’s in Logistics Management (2015) and Ma ster’s in Logistics Engineering Management (2018) from the Institute of Technology, East China Jiaotong University. He has published three pape rs. His research interests include ideological education, employ ment, and entrepreneurship. 1 Introduction M n Port Service Industry and Creative Culture of Zhejiang Province, Ningbo Digital-Intelligence Supply Chain Innovation Research Institute, Zhejiang Wanli University, Ningbo 315000, China Email: ch22298@sina.com Abstract: This study tackles the crucial pr oblem of forecasting employment anxiety in graduates through surpassing the constraints of traditional evaluation techniques that depend on static sel f-reports and ignore the dynamic social context. We present a multimodal dynamic graph neural network framework which fuses Smartphone-sensed behavi oural data and real-world physical interaction networks. We us e a bidirectional gated recurrent unit to encode the temporal behaviour, and we also have a dynamic graph attent ion to capture the changes in social support. Comprehensiv e evaluation on the StudentLife dataset shows that our approach outperforms stat e-of-the-art baselines significantly by reducing root mean square error by 12.5% from 5.82 to 5.09 and mean absolute error by 15.8% from 4.68 to 3.94 and ge tting a determination coefficient of 0.67. These results show that the fra mework works well at copying how individual behaviours and social forces wo rk together for mental health checks. Keywords: employment anxiety prediction; multimodal learning; graph neural networks; dynamic social netw orks; digital phenotyping. Reference to this paper should be made as follows: Ouyang, C. (2026) ‘Harnessing multimodal graph neural networks to pred ict graduate employment anxiety’, Int. J. Information and Communication Technology , Vol. 27, No. 22, pp.54–71. Biographical notes: Chenghui Ouyang is a Lecturer at the School of Logistics and E-Commerce, Zhejiang Wanli University. He earned his Bachelor’s in Logistics Management (2015) and Ma ster’s in Logistics Engineering Management (2018) from the Institute of Technology, East China Jiaotong University. He has published three pape rs. His research interests include ideological education, employ ment, and entrepreneurship. 1 Introduction Mental health problems of university students have turned into a severe public health problem worldwide. Among them, employment anxiety is the most common psychological stressor for graduation students. It has a major effect on their job hunting Harnessing multimodal graph neural networks 55 and career starting performance, and it is str ongly related to a number of physical and mental health issues, such as depression a nd sleep disorders (Li et al., 2022). Traditional psychological assessment is mainly based on retrospective self-report questionnaires. The most commonly used is the widely used perceived stress scale (PSS). However, these methods have their own limitations; they usually reflect users’ static psychological state at the time of completion, affected by recall bias and social desirability bias, which is hard to realise a continuous, objective, and prospective monitoring of anxiety (Kroenke et al., 2001). Conversely, it becomes necessary to establish a computational technique that can predict graduate employment anxiet y passively, dynamically, and accurately for the higher educational institution to promptly and effectively intervene and improve the guidance service. With the development of pervasive computing and AI technology, the use of passive sensor data generated by mobile devices such as mobile phones to evaluate mental health status is a brand-new research approach. In this field, the StudentLife study of Wang et al. (2014) is a milestone. By continually following smartphone sensor data (activity, sleep, calls, location, etc.) from 48 univer sity students and then using standardised psychological tests, this research found fo r the first time that there are significant connections between passive behaviour character istics and mental states such as stress and depression. Their work shows that we can actually tell how stressed people are from looking at their behaviour on a phone – stuff like not wanting to talk to other people as much as they used to, not sleeping as well as before, and just generally moving around less. In line with these studies, more and more advanced forms of machine learning like LSTMs and transformers that are able to r ecognise deeper pattern in behavioural time series data to improve predictability (Saeb et al., 2015; Bent et al., 2021). More recently, Zhou et al. (2024) adopted spatio-temporal GCNs to model students’ behavioural patterns within campus environments with a finer granularity, offering new insights into the environmental factors that lead to the crea tion of stress. All together, they form the dominant paradigm for computational psychological state assessment that is mostly dependent on analysing independent behavioural sequences. However, even though there has been some pr omising advances in this direction, one of the major limitations of such studies is that they tend to treat people as ‘islands’ in the process of information. It is ignoring a large part of the human brain: our social networks that we are connected to. Soci al support theory points to solid social bonds as important resource to lessen strain and uneasiness (C ohen and Wills, 1985). The core assumption that social support acts as a buffer against stress has been widely confirmed as universal across different cultural contexts. However, the specific sources, manifestations, and perceived efficacy of social support may indeed vary across cultures. For instance, within collectivist cultural contexts (such as East As ia), family and close primary groups may be regarded as more central sources of suppor t; whereas in individualistic cultural settings (such as North America), peers and voluntarily established social networks may play a more prominent role. Conducted within a West ern university environment, the findings of this study directly reflect the operational patterns of social support within that specific cultural context. Within the specific context of seeking a graduate job, peer-to-peer information exchange, emotional support, and even competition for a graduate position create a complex social environment that has a critical amplifying or offsetting impact on a graduate’s anxiety. Existing computational methods have been unable to properly model the social context in wh ich this takes place, severely hampering any ability to have an all-encompassing understanding and prediction of anxiety dynamics. 56 C. Ouyan g In recent years, with the emergence of GNNs, we have gained powerful technical tools for modelling these intricate social relationships (Jin, 2025). GNNs exhibit remarkable promise for handling relationa l data by means of the gathering of neighbourhood information utilising msg passing mechanisms (Jiang et al., 2019; Velickovic et al., 2017). In the field of computational mental health, some initial efforts have been made to apply GNNs on online social networks such as Twitter to detect a user’s depression risk (Zhao et al., 2022).However, these studies are based on static online ‘follow’ or ‘friend’ relationships that are often meager and contextless, and thus cannot truly represent the psychologically meanin gful face-to-face social interactions that actually happen in the real world. Graduate s who are located in a campus setting, their daily, offline physical interactions, like sharin g time with other people in a lab, dorm, or library, these are the main channels for social support exchange and emotional contagion. Currently, studies that are able to capture and analyse th ese real-world, off-line physical contact networks, and are tightly integrated into the individual’s behavioural modalities to predict psychological stress, have not been fully investigated. Filling this gap requires not only technological innovation but also a robust theoretical framework. This framework must translate psyc hological insights on social support into computable forms, thereby guiding model design and explaining its operational mechanisms. 2 Research on mental health computing and GNNs 2.1 Smartphone-based psychological assessment Digital phenotyping of mental health using passive smartphone sensor data has emerged as a research focus within computational ps ychiatry and pervasive computing. Pioneering work by Wang et al. (2014) demonstrated, using the StudentLife dataset, that behavioural characteristics extracted from mobile sensors – such as sleep duration, activity levels, activity radius, and social interaction frequency – exhibit statistically significant correlations with students’ self-reported st ress and depression scores. This supervised learning paradigm exhibits remarkable versatility and scalability. By substituting with corresponding annotated data (namely scor es from other psychological scales), the framework can be flexibly applied to screening and risk assessment for diverse mental health conditions, including depression, loneliness, substance abuse, and even post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD). Its co re strength lies in learning generalisable patterns associated with specific psychological constructs from diverse behavioural digital phenotypes. Such research typically models mental health prediction as a supervised learning task, where the objective function can be formalised as learning a mapping function f such that: () ii iyf=+ ∈ X (1) where yi denotes the psychological scale score of the ith user (e.g., PSS stress score), (1) (2) ( ), ,...,T ii i i= Xx x x denotes the behavioural feature sequence across T time windows, with representing the error term. Subsequent studies, such as Bent et al. (2021), employed more sophisticated temporal models like LSTM networks to better capture long-term dependencies in behaviour. The LSTM updates the cell state c t and hidden state ht Harnessing multimodal graph neural networks 57 through its gating mechanisms (input gate it, forget gate ft, output gate ot), with its core equations including: () 11 ,L S T M , ,tt t t t −− = hc xh c (2) Thereby achieving effectiv e encoding of the sequence Xi. However, the fundamental limitation of this research paradigm lies in its assumption that individuals are mutually independent. Model f learns solely from user i own historical behaviour, entirely disregarding the potential influence of the social network structure in which the user is embedded upon their psychological state. This contradicts the fundamental tenets of social support theory and constrains the comprehensive character isation of emotions possessing socially contagious traits, such as anxiety. 2.2 Applications of GNNs in mental health GNNs model relational structures through message-passing m , calls, location, etc.) from 48 univer sity students and then using standardised psychological tests, this research found fo r the first time that there are significant connections between passive behaviour character istics and mental states such as stress and depression. Their work shows that we can actually tell how stressed people are from looking at their behaviour on a phone – stuff like not wanting to talk to other people as much as they used to, not sleeping as well as before, and just generally moving around less. In line with these studies, more and more advanced forms of machine learning like LSTMs and transformers that are able to r ecognise deeper pattern in behavioural time series data to improve predictability (Saeb et al., 2015; Bent et al., 2021). More recently, Zhou et al. (2024) adopted spatio-temporal GCNs to model students’ behavioural patterns within campus environments with a finer granularity, offering new insights into the environmental factors that lead to the crea tion of stress. All together, they form the dominant paradigm for computational psychological state assessment that is mostly dependent on analysing independent behavioural sequences. However, even though there has been some pr omising advances in this direction, one of the major limitations of such studies is that they tend to treat people as ‘islands’ in the process of information. It is ignoring a large part of the human brain: