trainable weight matrix. The graph attention network (GAT) (Velickovic, et al., 2017) further introduces an attention coefficient. () () softmax LeakyReLU ||T ij j i j =  aW hW h α (4) Enabling node i to assign different weights when aggregating information from its neighbours () . ji∈ In the field of mental health , Ahmed et al. (2023) proposed a solution for identifying depressive symptoms in social media users, addressing the societal issue of depression. Employing GATs based on masked self-attention layers and incorporating top-level word expansion for sentiment vocabulary, the approach achieved an accuracy of 0.91 when applied to relevant Reddit data, while maintaining simplicity and interpretability. However, such research rests upon a critical universal assumption: the graph structure A relied upon is static and derived from online virtual social networks (e.g., ‘follow’ rela tionships). These static, virtua l connections fail to accurately reflect the dynamic nature of real-world social support. Among graduate cohorts, psychologically meaningful supportive interactions frequently occur during face-to-face offline engagements, with the intensity and frequency of these contact networks fluctuating markedly over time (e.g., during job-hunting seasons or exam weeks). Currently, research capable of characterising and leveraging such dynamic, physically co-located contact networks for psychological stress prediction remains a frontier gap. The recently proposed dynamic heterogeneous graph transformer by Wang (2023) offers a novel technical pathway for modelling these co mplex, time-evolving social interactions. 58 C. Ouyan g 2.3 Fusion strategies in multimodal learning Mental health itself is a complex construct shaped by the interplay of biological, psychological, and social factors, which naturally gives rise to multimodal learning approaches (Liu, 2025). Early research primar ily employed feature-le vel (early) fusion or decision-level (late) fusion strategies. The effectiveness of multimodal fusion is highly dependent on the quality and completeness of data across modalities. When data from a particular modality (such as social contact ne tworks) exhibits severe missing values or contains substantial noise, the performance of traditional strategies – such as simple concatenation or decision-level fusion – deteriorates sharply. This occurs because these approaches lack the capacity to dynamically adjust their reliance on different modalities. These further underscores the necessity of de veloping robust adaptive fusion mechanisms – such as the attention-based fusion employed herein – which automatically assign greater weight to more reliable information sources when data is suboptimal, thereby maintaining stable overall predictive perfor mance. Early fusion directly concatenates feature vectors from different modalities, zbehaviour and zsleep, into a single vector: early-fused [ behavior sleep] =⊕ zz z (5) Then input into a classifier. Late fusion, on the other hand, involves making separate predictions for each modality and then taking a weighted average of the results: ˆˆ 1M mm ym w y== (6) In his review on multimodal machine learning, Baltrušaitis et al. (2018 weeks). Currently, research capable of characterising and leveraging such dynamic, physically co-located contact networks for psychological stress prediction remains a frontier gap. The recently proposed dynamic heterogeneous graph transformer by Wang (2023) offers a novel technical pathway for modelling these co mplex, time-evolving social interactions. 58 C. Ouyan g 2.3 Fusion strategies in multimodal learning Mental health itself is a complex construct shaped by the interplay of biological, psychological, and social factors, which naturally gives rise to multimodal learning approaches (Liu, 2025). Early research primar ily employed feature-le vel (early) fusion or decision-level (late) fusion strategies. The effectiveness of multimodal fusion is highly dependent on the quality and completeness of data across modalities. When data from a particular modality (such as social contact ne tworks) exhibits severe missing values or contains substantial noise, the performance of traditional strategies – such as simple concatenation or decision-level fusion – deteriorates sharply. This occurs because these approaches lack the capacity to dynamically adjust their reliance on different modalities. These further underscores the necessity of de veloping robust adaptive fusion mechanisms – such as the attention-based fusion employed herein – which automatically assign greater weight to more reliable information sources when data is suboptimal, thereby maintaining stable overall predictive perfor mance. Early fusion directly concatenates feature vectors from different modalities, zbehaviour and zsleep, into a single vector: early-fused [ behavior sleep] =⊕ zz z (5) Then input into a classifier. Late fusion, on the other hand, involves making separate predictions for each modality and then taking a weighted average of the results: ˆˆ 1M mm ym w y== (6) In his review on multimodal machine learning, Baltrušaitis et al. (2018) systematically compared the strengths and w eaknesses of these strategies. However, when one of the ‘modalities’ comprises complex gr aph-structured data, these simple fusion approaches prove inadequate. They fail to adaptively learn the dynamically shifting relative importance of interactions between individual behavioural traits and their social network characteristics across different social contexts . For instance, when a model detects a user within a high-density supp ortive social circle, it should place greater reliance on the ‘buffering signals’ provided by the network modality. Conversely, when a user is socially isolated, their behavioural anomalies should be assigned higher weighting. Existing fusion methods lack this contextual awarene ss, hindering the precise modelling of social support’s moderating effects. In response, th e explainable cross-modal fusion framework developed by Wang et al. (2024) employs a gated attention mechanism to dynamically allocate contributions between modalities, prov iding crucial reference for our research. Consequently, developing an adaptive, dynamic cross-modal interaction mechanism that fuses individual behavioural sequences with dynamic social graph structures is pivotal to advancing this field and constitutes one of the core problems addressed in this study. 3 Construction of a multimodal dynamic GNN (MDGNN) model 3.1 Problem formulation We define the graduate psychological stress prediction problem as a node regression task based on dynamic graphs. Given a sequence of dynamic graphs: Harnessing multimodal graph neural networks 59 12, ,...,T =   (7) Each snapshot represents the state of studen ts’ social contacts within the time window t: (),,tt t= X   (8) where 12, ,...,N vv v= denotes a fixed set of nodes representing N students; εt denotes the set of edges at time t, whose adjacency matrix is ,NN t×∈A where element At,ij represents the co-occurrence duration or interaction frequency between students vi and vj within time window t; ND t×∈X is the node feature matrix, where each row ,ti tx represents the D-dimensional behavioural feature vector extracted from Smartphone sensor data for student vi within time window t. Our objective is to learn a mapping function: 12: , ,...,T f →y   (9) This function maps the dynamic graph sequence across the entire observation period onto the target variable N∈y for each node, namely the stud ent’s PSS score at term-end. This function f constitutes the MDGNN model we shall train. 3.2 Theoretical foundations and formalisation Our model design draws profound inspiration from social support theory and stress dynamics systems theory. We hypothesise that an individual’s stress state constitutes a time-evolving dynamic system, whose fluctuations are jointly influenced by internal stressors and external social buffering effects. We formalise this theory as a discrete-time dynamic equation: (1 ) ( ) ( ) ( ) ( )ii ii iSt St It Bt t+= +⋅ −⋅ + ∈ α β (10) where Si(t) denotes the stress level of student vi at time t; Ii(t) represents internal stressors (such as job-seeking setbacks or academic deadlines), which are indirectly encoded by behavioural modal data xt,i; Bi(t) denotes the social buffering effect, i.e., the stress-relieving influence derived from one’s social network; α and β are moderating coefficients; ∈i(t) is the random noise term. The social buffer effect Bi(t) is modelled as the weighted sum of all its social contacts: () ()() () () iii j j jtBt πtg z t ∈=⋅  (11) where ()it denotes the set of neighbours for node vi at time t; zj(t) represents the latent state of neighbour vj at time t, encoding its capacity or inc lination to provide support; the function g(⋅) serves as a transformation function; while πij(t) represents a dynamic, data-driven attention weight quan tifying the efficacy of neighbour vj support for vi at a specific time t. This theoretical framework directly guided the design of the dynamic graph attention mechanism in our subsequent model, enabling it not only to aggregate information but also to simulate the psychological processes of social support. Notably, 60 C. Ouyan g Grahek et al. (2021) independently validat ed the efficacy of a similar theoretical formalisation within the field of psychoco mputational research in their recent work. 3.3 MDGNN framework Our MDGNN model comprises the following core components, with its overall architecture illustrated in Figure 1. Figure 1 MDGNN framework (see online version for colours) Dynamic Social Contact Network Cohabitation time matrix sequence {A₁, A₂, ... , Aₜ} Physical contact frequency Intensity of social interaction Network Topology evolutionDynamic Social Contact Network Cohabitation time matrix sequence {A₁, A₂, ... , Aₜ} Physical contact frequency Intensity of