duce a top- kfocused loss to ensure the accuracy of identifying academically at-risk students. Extensive experiments were carried out on a large-scale real-world dataset, and we show that our approach substantially outperforms recently proposed methods for academic performance prediction. For the sake of reproducibility, our codes have been released at https://github. com/ZongJ1111/Academic-Performance-Prediction. Index Terms —Academic performance prediction, campus be- havior trajectory, convolutional neural networks, at-risk student identiﬁcation. I. I NTRODUCTION STudent outcomes are the prioritized factors for higher educational institutions, and highly correlated with their reputation. However, the risk of academic failure becomes an increasingly severe issue in education today. According to the US National Center for Education Statistics [1], more than 30% of college freshmen drop out after their ﬁrst year of college. Therefore, colleges constantly look for effective ways to enhance students’ learning experiences. Academic perfor- mance prediction aims to predict students’ future academic performance based on student-related information [2]. It not This work was supported by the National Natural Science Foundation of China under Grant 62077033 and Grant 61876098, by the National Key R&D Program of China under Grant 2018YFC0830100 and Grant 2018YFC0830102, and by the Fostering Project of Dominant Discipline and Talent Team of Shandong Province Higher Education Institutions. C. Cui is with the School of Computer Science and Technology, Shan- dong University of Finance and Economics, Jinan 250014, China (e-mail: crcui@sdufe.edu.cn). J. Zong, M. Chen, and Y . Yin are with the School of Software, Shandong University, Jinan 250101, China (e-mail: superzj1111@163.com; mchen@sdu.edu.cn; ylyin@sdu.edu.cn). Y . Ma is with the School of Computer Science and Technology, Shandong Jianzhu University, Jinan 250101, China (email: mayuling@mail.sdu.edu.cn). X. Wang is with the